ience. Examining the sources of this belief, Ian Copestake breaks new ground by tracing the enduring impact of Williams's youthful experience of Unitarianism on his poetry and arguing that Williams is a poet in an Emersonian tradition. Two chapters focus on Williams's long poem Paterson, arguing that its long gestation -- from 1927 to 1951 -- reflects its role asan ethical autobiography in progress. Copestake investigates sources that point to the ethical heart of Williams's poetry and to his lifelong belief that "It is difficult / to get the news from poems / yet men die miserably every day / for lack / of what is found there." Ian D. Copestake is a Lecturer at the University of Bamberg, Germany and editor of the William Carlos Williams Review.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aModern Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican poetry.  aEmersonian tradition.  aPaterson.  aUnitarianism.  aWilliam Carlos Williams.  acontemporary experience.  aethical autobiography.  anews from poems.  asimple language.  atwentieth century.  atwenty-first century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781571137234?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571137234423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571137234/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles